Tested with ts-node against this:

```
import { expect } from 'chai';

const obj = {
  a: {
    b: 1,
  },
  c: 2,
};
expect(obj).to.deep.nested.include({
  'a.b': 1,
  'c': 2,
});
```

This PR specifically adds `NextComponentType` and `AppComponentType` so they can be used in HOCs the same way we normally use `React.ComponentType`.

`NextContext.Component` is not a `React.ComponentType` but a `NextComponentType` instead, given it contains the Next.js specific lifecycle method `getInitialProps`:

![screen shot 2018-09-19 at 16 31 28](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/474603/45763950-83758c00-bc29-11e8-8a0b-763da8d02af8.png)

The `NextComponentType` is also needed for HOCs that receive Next.js page or app components. See [tests](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/29021/files#diff-b201442b6dd5bf2932ebee4743ea75c4R54) for examples on how to add types for those. E.g. this is similar to what `withRedux` does:

```tsx
const withExample = <P extends {}>(Page: NextComponentType<P & WithExampleProps, P>) =>
    class extends React.Component<P & WithExampleHocProps> {
        test: string;

        static async getInitialProps(ctx: NextContext) {
            const pageProps = Page.getInitialProps && (await Page.getInitialProps(ctx));

            // tslint:disable-next-line prefer-object-spread
            return Object.assign({}, pageProps, { test: "test" });
        }

        constructor(props: P & WithExampleHocProps) {
            super(props);
            this.test = props.test;
        }

        render() {
            return <Page {...this.props} example={this.test} />;
        }
    };
```

`<P>` is inferred to match the wrapped component `Initial Props`. The HOC component then adds `WithExampleHocProps` to itself and finally renders the wrapped component with its own initial props plus `WithExampleProps`.

This also updates the template types for `NextStatelessComponent` and `App` to receive a `Context` type instead of the `Query` for consistency with all the other generics and given that `NextContext` can receive a `Query` param already. This allows to define your own context type as well as your own query schema. /cc @kaw2k 

Finally, renamed and deprecated some types for consistency. E.g. `NextContext`/`NextAppContext`/`NextDocumentContext` and `AppProps`/`DocumentProps`.

